{
  "text": "It is possible to prove that freeness, monotonicity and IIA imply unanimity (see Chapter 3 of [CITATION_1] ). On the other hand, there are social welfare functions which are free, unanimous and IIA but not monotonic [CITATION_2] . Thus, unanimity and IIA does not imply freeness and monotonicity. Therefore a weaker version of Arrow's result on complete orders states that, with at least two voters and three outcomes, it is not possible to have at the same time freeness, monotonicity, IIA, and non-dictatorship [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "118896257",
